From March to August 1987, specimens were collected from 300 calves on 30 of the 42 dairy farms visited. Of the 300 calves, 131 had diarrhea, 16 had signs of respiratory disease, and three had both diarrhea and respiratory disease signs; 150 calves served as controls. Two hundred and four were Holstein, 81 Jersey, 1 Guernsey, 10 crosses of the preceding breeds, 2 Zebu cross, 1 Brown Swiss and 1 unknown. Nine were male calves, and 291 female. Twenty-six of 273 serum specimens (9.5%) were negative for immunoglobulins by the zinc sulfate turbidity test. (Serum specimens were not available from all calves. ) 


